WEBVTT

00:07.441 --> 00:10.476
JOHNNY: I am predator-proofing
my camp right now.

00:13.280 --> 00:16.682
More specifically,
this meat cache.

00:17.718 --> 00:20.819
And I'm going to be putting
these some extra stove pipe

00:20.855 --> 00:23.822
that I have, and I'm going
to wrap them around the tree.

00:24.158 --> 00:25.524
Further up, of course.

00:25.559 --> 00:27.092
Once they hit this
metal, their claws,

00:27.128 --> 00:30.796
they can't grip into the tree,
so it brings them right back

00:30.831 --> 00:33.465
to square one.

00:33.901 --> 00:36.001
Everything out here
has access to my fridge,

00:36.037 --> 00:38.837
whether I like it or not.

00:39.573 --> 00:41.940
The animals, they'll take
advantage of anything they see.

00:41.976 --> 00:43.509
If there's food laying around...

00:43.544 --> 00:44.943
Oh, yeah.

00:44.979 --> 00:47.413
They'll help themselves
to whatever they find.

00:48.015 --> 00:52.151
So, I had gotten a caribou,
and it was late in the evening,

00:52.186 --> 00:54.920
so I hung it up here.

00:56.057 --> 00:59.425
And I woke up the next day,
and it was gone.

01:01.062 --> 01:04.063
The bear grabbed the
caribou, ripped it down,

01:04.098 --> 01:06.432
drug it through all the brush,

01:06.467 --> 01:08.300
and it was ripped
open pretty good.

01:08.335 --> 01:11.470
It tore up the ribs and
spread the hindquarters apart,

01:11.505 --> 01:14.173
and there were bear
tracks around it,

01:14.208 --> 01:16.875
so it was pretty obvious
that it was a grizzly bear.

01:18.079 --> 01:20.145
At that point, the bear
has claimed that kill,

01:20.181 --> 01:22.381
so it's its property.

01:22.416 --> 01:24.783
And I felt like I was
trespassing around the caribou

01:24.819 --> 01:26.452
that I had shot at that point.

01:26.487 --> 01:28.654
It was an eerie feeling,
to know that, you know,

01:28.689 --> 01:31.824
that bear could be just
right over in the brush,
or in the bushes,

01:31.859 --> 01:35.661
and it would definitely defend
that kill with its life,

01:35.696 --> 01:37.996
and I'm not ready to die.

01:48.409 --> 01:49.908
I just worry a lot.

01:49.944 --> 01:53.412
This is my food
here, you know,

01:53.447 --> 01:57.282
if they get to the food,
it's, it'll be a tough time,

01:57.318 --> 01:59.118
especially with
these cold temperatures,

01:59.153 --> 02:01.753
to be well fed.

02:02.123 --> 02:04.590
I mean I eat, I eat
quite a bit of fat out here.

02:04.625 --> 02:08.527
It's amazing how my body
adapts to the environment,

02:08.562 --> 02:12.498
and since being out here,
it just craves fat.

02:14.935 --> 02:18.237
I'm a pretty lean guy.

02:18.272 --> 02:22.407
So, it's important to
safeguard the caribou
meat that I do have.

02:31.318 --> 02:32.818
(howling).

02:32.853 --> 02:34.820
Do you hear that?

02:34.855 --> 02:37.022
Wolves.

02:37.458 --> 02:39.925
(howling).

02:39.960 --> 02:42.861
It's probably about a
dozen wolves, at least.

02:44.765 --> 02:46.832
The wolves
concern me with Java.

02:46.867 --> 02:49.234
They come out here, and
they come around the camp,

02:49.270 --> 02:53.238
they try to lure
her away from me.

02:54.408 --> 02:56.708
And their goal is
to take her out,

02:56.744 --> 02:58.443
because they look at
her as competition.

02:58.479 --> 03:00.412
And they try to kind
of flirt with her,

03:00.447 --> 03:02.881
and pull her away from me,
in a way that makes them,

03:02.917 --> 03:05.083
like, not appear dangerous.

03:05.119 --> 03:07.553
And then, once
she's away from me,

03:07.588 --> 03:10.722
that's when they kind of
start to try to circle her.

03:10.758 --> 03:14.059
That's ultimately my
biggest fear with the wolves.

03:14.094 --> 03:16.795
They're not going to
access my meat up here
or anything like that.

03:16.830 --> 03:18.797
I don't have to
worry about that.

03:18.832 --> 03:21.366
I just worry about my dog.

03:22.069 --> 03:25.771
Java! Come here.
Come on. You stay.

03:25.806 --> 03:27.739
Everything out here
is trying to survive,

03:27.775 --> 03:29.508
including myself.

03:29.543 --> 03:32.244
Short term goals are to
stay warm, stay fed.

03:32.279 --> 03:34.580
Don't get killed.

03:39.820 --> 03:43.088
ALEX: I kind of got
impending doom over my
shoulders for the winter.

03:43.824 --> 03:46.058
It's getting colder.

03:46.093 --> 03:47.693
Pretty much whenever
there's a bad situation,

03:47.728 --> 03:50.195
it automatically
goes to worse.

03:52.433 --> 03:54.967
Now that it's winter,
and I just kind of
had a big cold snap,

03:55.002 --> 03:57.302
it was like, 30 below
for a couple days, uh,

03:57.338 --> 03:59.638
it means I spend
more time on my cabin.

03:59.673 --> 04:03.609
And just recently,
I noticed this should
be cool to the touch.

04:03.644 --> 04:05.177
When I got a hot
fire going on in here,

04:05.212 --> 04:06.778
this is getting
just as hot almost.

04:06.814 --> 04:09.081
It's actually, I touched it,
and it burnt me a little bit.

04:09.116 --> 04:11.583
It should not be that hot,
because it's going against the

04:11.619 --> 04:14.186
insulation in there,
and the wood.

04:14.221 --> 04:15.754
So, if this is
getting that hot,

04:15.789 --> 04:17.489
that's a huge fire hazard.

04:17.524 --> 04:20.125
I need to replace this,
basically this whole
chimney system,

04:20.160 --> 04:23.729
uh, which is gonna involve
tearing apart this wall,

04:23.764 --> 04:25.197
and everything.

04:25.232 --> 04:27.599
So, it's gonna be
kind of a big job.

04:31.171 --> 04:33.605
It's about to be the longest,
darkest days of winter.

04:33.641 --> 04:39.244
This is the time of year when
I'm making fires very often,

04:39.280 --> 04:41.413
sometimes all day long,
I have a fire going.

04:41.448 --> 04:44.149
I simply cannot survive
without a wood stove.

04:44.718 --> 04:46.852
Which means the risk of
setting my cabin on fire

04:46.887 --> 04:49.521
is extremely high.

04:51.125 --> 04:52.791
I made a small fire
early this morning,

04:52.826 --> 04:55.394
just to get a little
bit of heat in here.

04:55.429 --> 04:57.296
But the stove's
totally cool now.

04:57.331 --> 05:00.866
And, uh, I won't be making
another fire in here until

05:00.901 --> 05:03.568
I get my chimney replaced.

05:03.604 --> 05:06.038
My cabin is gonna
cool down rapidly.

05:06.073 --> 05:07.673
If my cabin freezes up,

05:07.708 --> 05:10.175
especially if all of my
water freezes, you know,

05:10.210 --> 05:11.443
then I'm left two options.

05:11.478 --> 05:13.779
Go haul more water,
or melt snow,

05:13.814 --> 05:15.414
which takes forever.

05:15.449 --> 05:17.783
It's just a
situation I wanna avoid.

05:17.818 --> 05:21.086
There's time pressure,
but I need to make
sure that I go slow,

05:21.121 --> 05:23.121
because if
I try to go fast,

05:23.157 --> 05:25.891
I'll just make a
mess of things.

05:30.597 --> 05:34.466
KALEB: It's important that
children learn the things that

05:34.501 --> 05:37.669
are necessary to make a
homestead like this function,

05:37.738 --> 05:41.606
so that they can succeed in the
future as they turn into adults,

05:41.642 --> 05:45.844
and become the next
generation of Alaskans.

06:00.894 --> 06:03.228
BRITTANY: Whatcha think, Ellie?
ELOVIE: Cool.

06:03.263 --> 06:06.231
KALEB: The smoker that I'm
building today is just a bunch

06:06.266 --> 06:10.168
of cinderblocks stacked
together in about a
four-foot square shape.

06:10.204 --> 06:12.771
You know that when
Grandpa built this smoker,

06:12.806 --> 06:16.641
his great idea was
to use welding rod
to hold the grates up.

06:17.144 --> 06:19.911
I'm hoping this smoker is an
opportunity to teach my kids a

06:19.947 --> 06:23.115
little more about the
fundamentals of building.

06:23.784 --> 06:25.484
BRITTANY: Keep going. Yeah!

06:25.519 --> 06:26.752
ELOVIE: Haha!

06:26.787 --> 06:28.320
KALEB: And it teaches them a
little more about taking pride

06:28.355 --> 06:30.389
in your work,
doing a good job.

06:30.424 --> 06:31.423
All right.

06:31.458 --> 06:33.091
Shall we try this
screen out, Ellie?

06:33.127 --> 06:34.326
ELOVIE: Yeah.

06:34.361 --> 06:36.495
KALEB: See if
Grandpa's ideas works.

06:36.530 --> 06:39.564
Look at that! It works.

06:39.600 --> 06:42.834
And then, getting to teach them
a little bit about food prep.

06:44.405 --> 06:45.971
Go get some firewood
and torch this off,

06:46.006 --> 06:49.775
and then, we can maybe go
hunt for some fresh game.

06:49.810 --> 06:51.143
You wanna go hunting?

06:53.747 --> 06:55.414
BRITTANY: Ellie, when
Mama was pregnant with you,

06:55.449 --> 06:58.650
Daddy and Gilbert and I
went ptarmigan hunting,

06:58.685 --> 07:01.086
and you were in my belly then!

07:02.489 --> 07:04.489
So, you have gone
ptarmigan hunting.

07:04.525 --> 07:06.458
When you were in
mommy's tummy!

07:06.493 --> 07:09.161
KALEB: Go head on out and get
some fresh meat to put in here,

07:09.196 --> 07:11.863
and while I'm out there,
the whole mountainside is

07:11.899 --> 07:15.467
covered in good alder that
we'll smoke the meat with.

07:15.502 --> 07:17.335
So, I'll bring some
of that back, too.

07:17.371 --> 07:20.038
BRITTANY: Cool.
Come on, Ellie, let's go.

07:20.641 --> 07:24.443
Elovie is always gung-ho
to try different things,

07:24.478 --> 07:26.945
including going
hunting with Kaleb.

07:26.980 --> 07:28.580
I love that, as
she's gotten older,

07:28.615 --> 07:30.782
she's actually
able to go with him.

07:30.818 --> 07:33.452
It's wonderful to be able to
see her grow into herself,

07:33.487 --> 07:36.121
and be able to
do these things.

07:39.793 --> 07:42.561
KALEB: Piper, stay home.
ELOVIE: Stay!

07:42.596 --> 07:45.397
KALEB: Elovie is gonna have
a unique opportunity today.

07:45.432 --> 07:47.632
She gets one on
one time with me,

07:47.668 --> 07:50.268
in the mountains,
doing what I love most,

07:50.304 --> 07:53.171
hunting wild game.

07:53.207 --> 07:56.174
There's no guarantees, I have
not been up to the bowl where

07:56.210 --> 07:57.776
we're going hunting.

07:57.811 --> 07:59.878
There should be a foot,
foot and a half of snow.

07:59.913 --> 08:02.447
And so, we're taking the
snow machine up there,

08:02.483 --> 08:03.782
and we'll just have
to look around,

08:03.817 --> 08:05.951
and see what we can find.

08:09.490 --> 08:14.159
MICHAEL: I take a lot
of pride training and
running a subsistence team.

08:14.194 --> 08:17.028
And so, what you see here,
is you see tradition.

08:17.064 --> 08:19.498
And the tradition is strong.

08:22.135 --> 08:27.138
(barking).

08:28.208 --> 08:30.909
Quiet down, you
little knuckleheads.

08:30.944 --> 08:32.777
You guys are nuts.

08:36.683 --> 08:40.151
You wanna be a sled dog?
Wanna go for a run?

08:42.289 --> 08:44.456
First run.

08:44.625 --> 08:47.125
Earlier today, the
winds come through.

08:47.160 --> 08:49.828
We had white out conditions.

08:49.863 --> 08:52.631
These trees were
snapping and cracking.

08:52.666 --> 08:55.901
I had a great big branch
fall off into the puppy lot.

08:55.936 --> 08:58.370
But things have settled down.

08:58.405 --> 09:00.872
The visibility has improved.

09:00.908 --> 09:02.340
I can actually see around me.

09:02.376 --> 09:04.609
The winds have
dropped down, and so,

09:04.645 --> 09:07.112
this is a perfect time to get
on the trail and start running

09:07.147 --> 09:10.048
these dogs on their first run.

09:10.450 --> 09:12.417
This is the dog
mushing season.

09:12.452 --> 09:14.085
The way I start
my training out,

09:14.121 --> 09:16.588
is I usually tie them up
to a sled with no weight,

09:16.623 --> 09:19.958
get the muscles moving,
get the tendons moving.

09:19.993 --> 09:21.626
Line up, come on.

09:21.662 --> 09:23.295
Line up. Stay.

09:23.330 --> 09:26.565
My goal on this first run is
just getting them back in tune

09:26.600 --> 09:28.300
with their commands.

09:28.335 --> 09:31.870
Getting them
psychologically prepared
to be back on the trail.

09:31.905 --> 09:34.439
Come on.

09:34.474 --> 09:36.575
So, I'm gonna hook up
three dogs at a time,

09:36.610 --> 09:38.910
that's about a
two-mile run total.

09:38.946 --> 09:41.079
Short trips...

09:41.114 --> 09:42.447
Stay!

09:42.482 --> 09:44.783
Actually help the dogs focus.

09:44.818 --> 09:47.619
Eventually, we do back
to back five milers.

09:47.654 --> 09:49.220
Ten milers.

09:49.256 --> 09:51.590
You know, you gotta crawl,
walk, and then, run.

09:51.625 --> 09:53.825
And so, this is
the crawl phase.

09:53.860 --> 09:56.861
Whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa.

09:57.664 --> 10:01.032
Go get 'em! Hyah! Hyah!

10:02.703 --> 10:05.637
Go get 'em! Hyah!
Hyah! Hyah! Hyah!

10:05.672 --> 10:08.440
Good boys.

10:10.711 --> 10:13.111
These dogs, they love
to be out on the trail.

10:13.146 --> 10:15.947
Come on.
Good boys.

10:15.983 --> 10:19.684
The genetics of the
Malamute, they've been
bred by indigenous people

10:19.720 --> 10:23.888
of the Northwest Arctic for
hundreds of generations

10:23.924 --> 10:27.192
to be kind, courteous...

10:27.227 --> 10:28.493
Gee over.

10:28.528 --> 10:30.328
Powerful, hearty animals.

10:30.364 --> 10:33.531
Awoo!

10:34.968 --> 10:38.637
I can cover 20 to 30
miles a day with these dogs,

10:38.672 --> 10:41.706
hauling 800 pounds of stuff.

10:41.742 --> 10:43.408
Straight ahead.

10:43.443 --> 10:45.677
For me, being an
East Coast Indian,

10:45.712 --> 10:48.680
this is a very
natural way of travel.

10:48.715 --> 10:52.951
It's in my blood, it's
in my ancestors' blood.

10:52.986 --> 10:56.321
Mushing was the way
that things were done.

10:56.356 --> 10:58.423
Whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa.

10:58.458 --> 11:01.860
Whoa!

11:05.165 --> 11:08.099
I'm sorry, guys, your trail.
It's blocked up.

11:19.246 --> 11:20.879
MICHAEL: Whoa, whoa,
whoa, whoa, whoa.

11:20.914 --> 11:23.982
Halt. Whoa!

11:25.318 --> 11:28.153
Oh, shoot.

11:28.522 --> 11:30.755
The trail, it's blocked up.

11:30.791 --> 11:33.291
We got two trees down.

11:35.495 --> 11:37.062
This is a little
bit of a problem.

11:37.097 --> 11:39.197
This is my loop that
takes me down to the river,

11:39.232 --> 11:40.965
it gets them their first hill.

11:41.001 --> 11:42.967
Once you start miling them up,
you gotta keep 'em going,

11:43.003 --> 11:45.403
keep 'em going,
every single day.

11:45.439 --> 11:47.138
A couple of trees down over
the trail, it happens.

11:47.174 --> 11:49.808
But unfortunately,
it's the beginning of
the training season.

11:49.843 --> 11:51.409
I can't be
stopped up for this,

11:51.445 --> 11:54.746
so this has gotta
be cleared out.

11:55.582 --> 11:58.149
That's a pretty
violent snap on that tree.

11:58.185 --> 12:00.452
It's not rotten in the
middle, it's a good piece.

12:00.487 --> 12:03.621
I'll buck that
one up as firewood,

12:03.657 --> 12:05.657
and clear it off the trail.

12:05.692 --> 12:08.893
This next one here,
significantly larger.

12:08.929 --> 12:10.995
It's gotta be about
two foot at the base.

12:11.031 --> 12:12.530
I'm making a note.

12:12.566 --> 12:16.401
I need a chainsaw mill,
a small firewood saw.

12:16.436 --> 12:18.069
(barking).

12:18.105 --> 12:20.205
These dogs are really anxious,
they got a lot of energy.

12:20.240 --> 12:22.674
All right, let's get
you turned around.

12:22.709 --> 12:24.876
Go get 'em!
Hyah! Hyah! Hyah!

12:24.911 --> 12:27.178
Good boys.

12:31.451 --> 12:34.919
JOHNNY: I'm living in a place
where humans don't really live.

12:36.022 --> 12:38.523
It's up to me to figure
out how to live out here.

12:38.558 --> 12:40.525
There's not a lot of
second chances that I get,

12:40.560 --> 12:43.628
so I kind of gotta figure it
out the first time around.

12:50.637 --> 12:53.037
Hey, Java, I thought
you were getting the
tool bag for me, huh?

12:53.073 --> 12:55.507
Carry your own weight,
or do you just wanna sit
around and eat all day?

12:57.144 --> 13:00.478
<i>NARRATOR: Having lost</i>
<i>valuable meat to a bear</i>
<i>who came into his camp,</i>

13:00.514 --> 13:04.349
<i>Johnny must protect his</i>
<i>property from anymore damage.</i>

13:04.818 --> 13:07.252
<i>In order to keep</i>
<i>himself and his dog safe,</i>

13:07.287 --> 13:11.289
<i>he must secure any</i>
<i>openings to his cabin.</i>

13:11.958 --> 13:15.093
JOHNNY: You know, a bear
will get into a cabin
if it wants to get in.

13:15.128 --> 13:17.495
They're a lot smarter
than we make them out to be.

13:17.531 --> 13:19.664
But the goal is to
hide this window,

13:19.699 --> 13:21.966
and it doesn't know
there's a window here.

13:22.002 --> 13:25.336
And that's, to me,
outsmarting the bear.

13:30.644 --> 13:33.745
Go ahead, Java.
Get it. There she goes.

13:35.482 --> 13:39.751
She kind of cleans up all
of the construction scraps.

13:39.786 --> 13:42.187
I'm not complaining.

13:42.322 --> 13:46.291
These two pieces will go,
one here and one here.

13:46.760 --> 13:49.260
I'm gonna cut these
shutters to size,

13:49.296 --> 13:53.298
and they'll essentially
be fixed to these two
vertical pieces.

13:53.333 --> 13:56.601
So then, it's just one solid
piece that I just put right up

13:56.636 --> 13:59.070
into this space.

13:59.105 --> 14:00.572
The little projects
that I do out here,

14:00.607 --> 14:01.739
they keep me going.

14:01.775 --> 14:03.541
They keep me positive.

14:03.577 --> 14:06.211
They keep me getting
out of bed every day.

14:06.246 --> 14:09.881
And if I didn't have
little projects to do,

14:09.916 --> 14:12.884
then, you know, it'd
be boring out here.

14:12.919 --> 14:15.653
And I'm not looking
for a boring life.

14:15.689 --> 14:19.457
This is the last
nail for this one.

14:24.030 --> 14:25.196
Nice.

14:25.232 --> 14:27.298
That's a nice, snug fit.

14:27.334 --> 14:30.902
Yeah, I feel a little
safer leaving camp
for longer durations.

14:32.405 --> 14:34.239
The wildlife out
here is abound.

14:34.274 --> 14:36.875
There are critters everywhere.

14:36.910 --> 14:38.910
But, you know, it's like, be
careful what you wish for,

14:38.945 --> 14:41.512
because I've always wanted to
see a lot of these animals,

14:41.548 --> 14:43.248
but I'm seeing a lot of them.

14:43.283 --> 14:45.850
And, you know, every day, it's
like a different animal is

14:45.886 --> 14:47.719
trying to present a
challenge for me.

14:47.754 --> 14:50.088
Java. You wanna go eat?

14:50.123 --> 14:51.556
Come on, let's call it a day.

14:51.591 --> 14:53.858
Come on!

15:00.066 --> 15:01.633
ALEX: When it's cold,
it's cold.

15:01.668 --> 15:04.569
And it stays cold
for a long time.

15:04.604 --> 15:06.738
When it's 40 below
or 50 below outside,

15:06.773 --> 15:09.207
you gotta do a lot
of work to stay warm.

15:23.790 --> 15:25.256
It's pretty dangerous.

15:25.292 --> 15:27.625
I mean, the falling ice tells
you it's way above freezing,

15:27.661 --> 15:29.494
is what it tells you.

15:29.529 --> 15:31.963
Redoing my
chimney is essential.

15:31.998 --> 15:35.033
But it's also gonna
be inherently risky.

15:35.068 --> 15:38.569
My roof is extremely steep,
and it's definitely not safe

15:38.605 --> 15:40.605
for me to just be
standing on a ladder,

15:40.640 --> 15:43.207
doing this kind of
work, unprotected.

15:43.242 --> 15:45.243
If I start to fall,
there's nothing, you know,

15:45.278 --> 15:47.111
there's no, nothing
to catch me on.

15:47.147 --> 15:49.113
So I'll fall all the way down.

15:49.149 --> 15:51.716
So, I need a rope to
hold the, you know,

15:51.751 --> 15:53.918
going over to hold the
ladder from the other side,

15:53.954 --> 15:56.421
so that it can't swing.

15:56.456 --> 15:58.389
And then, also a
rope to hold myself,

15:58.425 --> 16:01.059
uh, on the other side.

