Basically, I'll have a rope
going across the roof of the

16:04.364 --> 16:06.864
cabin to a tree
on the other side.

16:06.900 --> 16:08.866
The rope will allow
me to work safely,

16:08.902 --> 16:12.503
work confidently, without having
to worry about falling off.

16:12.539 --> 16:14.872
I'll have a harness
that I can clip into it.

16:14.908 --> 16:18.609
That way, there's a nice
tight rope holding me.

16:18.645 --> 16:21.312
So this way, if
I slip or fall,

16:21.348 --> 16:24.415
I'll just lean on the rope.

16:25.585 --> 16:27.585
In order to set up my
kind of rope safety system,

16:27.620 --> 16:29.921
I do have to go up
the ladder unprotected,

16:29.956 --> 16:32.657
and throw a rope over.

16:32.692 --> 16:37.028
I got a heavy iron
shackle on one end to
give it some weight.

16:51.311 --> 16:52.810
I need to kind of
wind up a little more,

16:52.846 --> 16:53.978
which makes me nervous.

16:54.014 --> 16:56.581
I'm working on a ladder on
the side of an icy roof.

16:58.551 --> 17:00.385
You know, I don't wanna fall.

17:00.420 --> 17:02.220
This might be the most
dangerous kind of part,

17:02.255 --> 17:04.889
is just setting up my anchor.

17:06.493 --> 17:08.559
This is one of the situations
where it's not enough that

17:08.595 --> 17:10.094
I just try hard.

17:10.130 --> 17:14.065
I have to do it right, because
if I get injured out here, uh,

17:14.100 --> 17:16.501
even, you know, a
relatively minor injury that

17:16.536 --> 17:19.404
might not be a big deal
if I got hurt in the city,

17:19.439 --> 17:22.073
out here, it can be
a death sentence.

17:22.108 --> 17:25.043
This (bleep) heavy.

17:25.078 --> 17:27.278
(bleep). (bleep).

17:37.624 --> 17:41.059
It's definitely not safe for me
to just be standing on a ladder,

17:41.094 --> 17:42.994
doing this kind of
work, unprotected.

17:43.029 --> 17:44.562
Second time.

17:44.597 --> 17:46.464
But, you know, any
time I'm working alone,

17:46.499 --> 17:48.766
a lot of my time is
spent figuring out all these

17:48.802 --> 17:50.735
different safety systems.

17:50.770 --> 17:53.204
Get the hell off
this death trap.

17:53.239 --> 17:54.972
Now I just gotta
find a good tree,

17:55.008 --> 17:57.108
something nice and solid
to tie my anchor off of.

17:57.143 --> 17:59.377
Something that will
hold my weight if I fall.

17:59.412 --> 18:02.447
There's my rope.

18:02.482 --> 18:04.549
And now I can go set up
the end of the rope that

18:04.584 --> 18:06.918
I will be connected to.

18:06.953 --> 18:11.055
Of course, which I
always wanna do is test it.

18:11.091 --> 18:16.894
So, it should be able to
adjust it as I climb up,

18:16.930 --> 18:20.031
and it will hold my
weight if I fall.

18:20.600 --> 18:22.667
I'm focused on doing
this as safe as I can,

18:22.702 --> 18:25.670
but I got a lot of things
kind of fighting against me.

18:25.705 --> 18:27.672
I got this cold snow
blowing in my face.

18:27.707 --> 18:31.242
Just have the steepness
and the slickness of
this metal roof.

18:31.277 --> 18:32.610
Here it comes.

18:32.645 --> 18:36.781
At this point, my body is pretty
exhausted, but, you know,

18:36.816 --> 18:39.951
I'm still a long ways
from finished with this job.

18:39.986 --> 18:41.552
So, there's no
turning back now,

18:41.588 --> 18:43.855
because now, I don't
have a stove anymore.

18:50.063 --> 18:53.464
MICHAEL: You can't just stop
because something is strenuous.

18:56.269 --> 18:58.002
You gotta keep going.

18:58.037 --> 19:00.371
And so, that's
part of life up here.

19:01.207 --> 19:06.277
Get 'em! Get 'em!
Go get 'em! Good girl!

19:06.312 --> 19:08.646
Look at you go!

19:08.681 --> 19:11.015
All right.

19:14.154 --> 19:17.255
Right out that way
is my five-mile loop.

19:17.290 --> 19:18.656
I gotta get on that.

19:18.691 --> 19:20.558
These dogs have
to keep miling up.

19:20.593 --> 19:23.027
It's time for that
first winter caribou hunt,

19:23.062 --> 19:26.097
and these dogs are
my transportation.

19:26.132 --> 19:28.733
It's very important,
they gotta keep running.

19:28.768 --> 19:32.637
And that will prevent injuries
on the trails during expedition.

19:33.006 --> 19:35.540
I'm gonna go ahead, fire
up my little chainsaw.

19:35.575 --> 19:37.742
Then I'm gonna try to
clear out all this old,

19:37.777 --> 19:40.978
rotten willow.

19:48.955 --> 19:52.990
It seems like I am
attached by a dummy cord
to this darn chainsaw.

19:53.393 --> 19:55.226
What a mess!

19:55.261 --> 19:57.361
I bought it used
for next to nothing,

19:57.397 --> 20:00.631
and it has handled year after
year after year of cutting.

20:03.703 --> 20:07.104
The winds are picking up.

20:07.140 --> 20:12.176
I actually don't like
working around these treetops.

20:12.478 --> 20:15.313
A 60, 70, 80 mile an hour
gust will come through,

20:15.348 --> 20:17.915
and just snap these trees
like they're toothpicks.

20:18.618 --> 20:21.352
Gonna have to hurry
up and clear this out.

20:25.592 --> 20:26.824
Look at that.

20:26.859 --> 20:28.993
My five-mile loop
