20:29.028 --> 20:32.663
I just bucked up that
small tree as firewood.

20:32.699 --> 20:36.667
That big tree, I'm just
gonna mill it up real
quick with my saw mill.

20:36.703 --> 20:39.737
It's gonna make
some nice lumber.

20:40.273 --> 20:41.906
And so, I got this
ladder brought out here,

20:41.941 --> 20:43.274
and this is just
to act as a guide,

20:43.309 --> 20:45.643
so my first cut will
be somewhat straight,

20:45.678 --> 20:48.279
and I can continue to cut this
two and a half inches thick

20:48.314 --> 20:51.382
the whole way down.

20:55.421 --> 20:57.922
This thing is an
absolute beast.

20:57.957 --> 21:00.625
Lot of work involved,
but if you do the work,

21:00.660 --> 21:03.461
you don't have to buy
store-bought lumber.

21:04.297 --> 21:06.464
I spent my whole life
working, working, working,

21:06.499 --> 21:09.100
and we're just
programmed to desire

21:09.135 --> 21:12.370
all these things that we
know we can't afford.

21:12.405 --> 21:15.106
That's unsustainable
for the human spirit.

21:15.141 --> 21:17.808
So, if I have to do a little
physical labor, big deal.

21:17.844 --> 21:22.179
It is liberating, not feeding
all these greedy systems.

21:23.650 --> 21:25.950
All right. First cut.

21:27.720 --> 21:30.388
Beautiful piece right there.

21:30.423 --> 21:32.490
I'll make a nice
bench out of that.

21:32.525 --> 21:35.993
All that brush seemed
like an impenetrable
barrier in the moment,

21:36.029 --> 21:37.728
but after doing
a little bit of work,

21:37.764 --> 21:39.563
I've got a nice
load of firewood,

21:39.599 --> 21:41.632
and I'll have slabs.

21:41.668 --> 21:44.335
It ended up turning
into an amazing situation,

21:44.370 --> 21:46.704
where a barrier
became an asset.

21:47.407 --> 21:50.875
But right now, the winds are
picking up something fierce.

21:50.910 --> 21:53.244
I wanna get this done
and get outta here.

22:03.389 --> 22:06.490
KALEB: Living out here, I have
to go out in the woods and

22:06.526 --> 22:08.559
harvest the meat,
process the meat,

22:08.594 --> 22:10.861
and then, I have
to preserve it.

22:10.897 --> 22:14.231
Whatever method is used,
I personally have to do.

22:20.073 --> 22:22.273
These tracks are
all old, Ellie.

22:22.308 --> 22:24.308
Check out all those
tracks over there, okay?

22:25.912 --> 22:28.479
I'm heading out into the
mountains to hunt ptarmigan,

22:28.514 --> 22:30.548
and I get to go teach my
daughter a little bit about

22:30.583 --> 22:33.317
hunting wild game.

22:33.353 --> 22:36.020
Stand up.

22:36.055 --> 22:37.922
You're doing great, Ellie.

22:37.957 --> 22:41.025
Ptarmigan are a
small grouse species.

22:41.060 --> 22:43.127
They usually live up
in the high country.

22:43.162 --> 22:44.595
They turn white
in the wintertime,

22:44.630 --> 22:46.630
so they're
extremely hard to see.

22:46.666 --> 22:50.301
Usually the only reason
you see them is by
looking for shapes.

22:50.770 --> 22:52.436
You have to learn the
shape of a ptarmigan,

22:52.472 --> 22:54.905
and if you can learn that,
you can find them.

22:54.941 --> 22:56.540
Look at these
ptarmigan tracks!

22:56.576 --> 22:58.876
These are kind of old, though.

22:58.911 --> 23:00.244
ELOVIE: How?

23:00.279 --> 23:01.879
KALEB: See how they look like
there's a little bit of snow

23:01.914 --> 23:03.414
in the bottom of them?

23:03.449 --> 23:05.149
It snowed two days ago.

23:05.184 --> 23:07.318
So these ptarmigan were up
here when it was snowing.

23:07.353 --> 23:10.721
And they've flown
off somewhere else.

23:12.091 --> 23:14.525
We need to go find some
more tracks somewhere else.

23:14.560 --> 23:16.894
Where maybe they've been
a little bit sooner.

23:16.929 --> 23:19.430
All right, let's go.

23:30.209 --> 23:33.277
Wow, Ellie.

23:34.313 --> 23:35.946
ELOVIE: Dad,
what are you doing?

23:35.982 --> 23:38.048
KALEB: Need to get
my binoculars out.

23:38.084 --> 23:40.618
ELOVIE: Can I help you also?

23:44.524 --> 23:47.391
KALEB: Look at that!
ELOVIE: Whoa.

23:58.738 --> 24:00.204
ELOVIE: Yeah.
KALEB: Through the binoculars?

24:00.239 --> 24:01.472
ELOVIE: Yup.

24:02.809 --> 24:03.808
KALEB: Yup.

24:05.478 --> 24:07.678
KALEB: Elovie just loved
seeing the moose today.

24:07.713 --> 24:09.146
They're just
wintering up there.

24:09.182 --> 24:10.881
They're way up in
the high country.

24:10.917 --> 24:14.018
And they'll stay up there until
the snow starts to get deep,

24:14.053 --> 24:16.353
and it pushes them
down the mountain.

24:16.389 --> 24:19.056
Ellie, it's pretty cool seeing
stuff move around up here.

24:19.091 --> 24:20.858
We've seen old
ptarmigan tracks.

24:20.893 --> 24:23.894
But so far, we're
not really seeing any,

24:23.930 --> 24:26.430
anything fresh
for ptarmigan, so.

24:30.803 --> 24:32.870
KALEB: Yeah, we
can't do that right now.

24:32.905 --> 24:34.405
ELOVIE: When?

24:34.440 --> 24:36.040
KALEB: I know, it's
pretty exciting seeing the
moose, though, isn't it?

24:38.611 --> 24:40.277
KALEB: We can shoot
the moose in September.

24:42.482 --> 24:43.647
KALEB: Oh, it's not sad.

24:43.683 --> 24:46.083
There's a reason
for hunting seasons.

24:46.118 --> 24:48.486
If you just went and killed
all the animals because you

24:48.521 --> 24:51.355
could hunt year-round then
there'd be nothing left,

24:51.390 --> 24:55.493
and we wouldn't be able to use
that resource in the future.

24:55.528 --> 24:58.028
Today was a good opportunity to
teach my daughter a little bit

24:58.064 --> 25:01.732
about conservation,
and we have to be
responsible stewards.

25:02.768 --> 25:05.703
And always remember that if we
want this to be here tomorrow,

25:05.738 --> 25:08.672
we need to be very careful
about our actions today.

25:08.708 --> 25:10.508
Check out the moose scat.

25:10.543 --> 25:12.543
ELOVIE: That is poop.

25:12.578 --> 25:14.011
KALEB: It's been
here a couple days.

25:14.046 --> 25:15.379
You think it's the
same moose we just saw?

25:15.414 --> 25:16.447
ELOVIE: Uh-huh.

25:16.482 --> 25:17.781
KALEB: Yeah, I bet so, too.

25:17.817 --> 25:19.884
It looks like he's been
living on the hillside
here for a few days.

25:19.919 --> 25:21.285
ELOVIE: Maybe.

25:21.320 --> 25:23.320
KALEB: I saw all sorts
of beds on the road.

25:23.356 --> 25:26.056
I think he's just
hangin' out up here,

25:26.092 --> 25:27.191
enjoying the view.

25:27.226 --> 25:28.292
What do you think?

25:28.327 --> 25:30.094
ELOVIE: Yeah.
KALEB: It's pretty gorgeous.

25:30.129 --> 25:33.731
ELOVIE: Uh-huh.
KALEB: Well.

25:33.766 --> 25:37.067
So, it might be time to
head down the mountain and
get our alder firewood.

25:37.103 --> 25:39.236
Ready to go do that?

25:39.272 --> 25:40.538
ELOVIE: Yeah.

25:40.573 --> 25:42.740
KALEB: All right. Let's go.

25:43.342 --> 25:45.643
We might not have been
successful with our
little ptarmigan hunt,

25:45.678 --> 25:50.214
which really depends on your
definition of success.

25:50.249 --> 25:51.815
I would consider it
success because I had a

25:51.851 --> 25:55.252
great afternoon with my
daughter in the mountains.

26:03.362 --> 26:05.863
Just sit there and watch
while I get some alders,

26:05.898 --> 26:06.997
and you will cool off.

26:07.033 --> 26:08.132
'Kay?

26:08.167 --> 26:11.402
Fortunately, we plan ahead,
and we have meat in the

26:11.437 --> 26:14.138
freezer from our
last hunting season,

26:14.173 --> 26:16.006
that we can call upon
to put in the smoker,

26:16.042 --> 26:18.809
instead of what we
attempted to harvest today.

26:18.844 --> 26:22.079
All right, Ellie, think that's
enough to smoke some meat?

26:22.114 --> 26:23.280
ELOVIE: Let's, let's boogie!

26:23.316 --> 26:26.116
KALEB: Let's boogie!

26:27.486 --> 26:29.119
Apparently,
you're ready to go.

26:29.155 --> 26:31.922
ELOVIE: Let's go!
KALEB: Let's go.

