And that's the
right, right foot,

32:04.189 --> 32:06.490
and that's the
left foot there.

32:06.525 --> 32:09.326
And he's moving, he's
moving toward my camp.

32:09.828 --> 32:12.162
Makes you think.

32:12.765 --> 32:14.698
You know, I've been, I've
been waitin' so long for it to

32:14.733 --> 32:17.301
start snowing so I could see
all of the tracks and know

32:17.336 --> 32:19.236
what's hanging around my camp.

32:19.271 --> 32:20.704
It's a little bit more
than I thought it was,

32:20.739 --> 32:24.975
to be honest, so, um, yeah,
time to get to this latch

32:25.010 --> 32:27.844
before, before
that sun goes down.

32:30.482 --> 32:32.115
Just gotta find about a one,
one-and-a-half-inch diameter,

32:32.184 --> 32:35.986
uh, little spruce tree.

32:36.021 --> 32:39.589
It'll act as the, the
piece that goes in the door.

32:39.625 --> 32:42.292
This one here might work.

32:44.730 --> 32:47.364
I really enjoy
working with my hands.

32:47.399 --> 32:49.933
To, to have a thought, and
to put it down on paper,

32:49.969 --> 32:52.536
and then, take it from
paper, and to apply it,

32:52.571 --> 32:55.172
and actually build it,
is very, very satisfying.

32:55.207 --> 32:57.140
So the plan for the
latch is to take,

32:57.176 --> 33:01.912
uh, two pieces, put 'em up.

33:04.984 --> 33:08.385
Spruce, I'm gonna
have to whittle down.

33:08.787 --> 33:10.554
Probably about 50%.

33:10.589 --> 33:13.890
And that's gonna slide
in and out of that
little box that I make.

33:13.926 --> 33:16.760
And I'll have a hole in the
side of this doorjamb that

33:16.795 --> 33:19.363
this will go into.

33:19.431 --> 33:22.733
Little handle, and
it'll slide in and out.

33:25.104 --> 33:29.673
You know, I think people tend
to go toward other humans when

33:29.708 --> 33:31.942
they wanna feel
like they belong.

33:31.977 --> 33:35.679
But I don't need people
out here to feel like
I belong to something.

33:35.714 --> 33:37.381
I feel like I
belong to this, uh,

33:37.416 --> 33:39.750
this ecosystem,
this environment,

33:39.785 --> 33:41.018
and all the animals.

33:41.053 --> 33:42.285
Nature.

33:42.321 --> 33:44.621
You know, having the bear that
comes around here at night,

33:44.656 --> 33:46.957
I'm a part of that
bear's life now,

33:46.992 --> 33:49.259
and it's kind of
become a part of me.

33:49.294 --> 33:50.861
We have this
weird relationship.

33:50.896 --> 33:54.097
You know, whose, whose
turf is it at what time?

33:54.132 --> 33:57.567
It's like a, a weird respect.

33:57.603 --> 33:59.903
But also, you can't let your
guard down either because

33:59.938 --> 34:02.105
that bear will
capitalize on, you know,

34:02.141 --> 34:04.141
taking my food.

34:04.176 --> 34:07.110
Possibly even turning me into
a meal or definitely Java.

34:11.650 --> 34:12.682
Let's give it the test.

34:12.718 --> 34:13.683
Java, come here!

34:13.719 --> 34:16.620
Java, come on!
Java, come on!

34:16.655 --> 34:18.922
You hear her scratching.

34:18.957 --> 34:21.992
Looks like the, looks like
the latch is doing its job.

34:22.027 --> 34:23.727
I hold myself
accountable out here.

34:23.762 --> 34:25.262
It's up to me to
get things done.

34:25.297 --> 34:26.863
Yeah, I'm pretty
happy with it.

34:26.898 --> 34:29.533
Works pretty good.

34:29.568 --> 34:31.768
You have to know how
to apply yourself.

34:31.804 --> 34:35.472
You gotta be confident,
but you can't be arrogant
or cocky either.

34:35.507 --> 34:37.674
And kind of have the
wisdom to know the difference,

34:37.709 --> 34:40.143
or you won't make it.

34:40.179 --> 34:42.279
What do you say, Java?

34:42.314 --> 34:46.483
You wanna go walk out on
the lake or something?

34:46.518 --> 34:47.584
Come on!

34:47.619 --> 34:48.919
Let's go walk out on the ice.

34:48.954 --> 34:51.421
Hmm? Come on!

34:59.531 --> 35:01.798
ALEX: A challenge comes,
I just face it.

35:01.834 --> 35:03.667
I just do my best.

35:03.735 --> 35:05.802
You know, I'm still here.
I'm still alive.

35:05.838 --> 35:08.805
Nobody can say I'm a
failure until I'm dead.

35:20.319 --> 35:21.585
It's a really
good thing I, uh,

35:21.620 --> 35:24.488
took my chimney down now
because all this creosote

35:24.523 --> 35:27.124
inside, if that
gets hot enough,

35:27.159 --> 35:28.625
it'll set on fire.

35:28.660 --> 35:30.861
I can see that there is, uh,
a bit of heat damage in here.

35:30.896 --> 35:33.296
So that's, uh, a
major warning sign.

35:33.332 --> 35:35.098
If it kept going on like that,
there would definitely have

35:35.134 --> 35:36.733
been a fire at some point.

35:36.768 --> 35:39.302
So, it's a good thing
I'm replacing this.

35:39.338 --> 35:41.972
You little son of a bitch.

35:42.574 --> 35:44.307
All this work I have to
do, everything's kind of

35:44.343 --> 35:46.877
conspiring against me to, to
make this job more dangerous

35:46.912 --> 35:48.712
than it has to be.

35:48.780 --> 35:51.515
You know, trying to lift and
haul heavy awkward things

35:51.550 --> 35:53.750
on a steep roof.

35:53.785 --> 35:55.685
I'm using sharp power tools.

35:55.721 --> 35:59.089
And I'm also
working in the dark.

36:01.093 --> 36:03.360
Okay. There you go.

36:03.395 --> 36:04.995
I can see the light at
the end of the tunnel.

36:05.030 --> 36:08.231
The final step is to get this
eight-foot length stove pipe.

36:08.267 --> 36:10.800
Lift this heavy
thing up, and then,

36:10.836 --> 36:13.336
carefully guide it
into the flashing,

36:13.372 --> 36:16.106
so that it rests on the
stovepipe underneath.

36:21.880 --> 36:23.947
Come on.

36:24.950 --> 36:26.983
It wants to tip either way.

36:27.019 --> 36:30.620
How do I prevent
it from doing that?

36:30.656 --> 36:33.590
Uh, once I get, I can get
it to here, that's fine.

36:33.625 --> 36:36.793
It starts to want sliding,
to slide either way.

36:36.828 --> 36:38.228
I just don't
want it to do that,

36:38.263 --> 36:39.596
because I don't,
I, it's too heavy,

36:39.631 --> 36:43.867
I won't be able to just
easily get the control of it.

36:47.706 --> 36:49.406
It's just I don't have any
control over the upper end,

36:49.441 --> 36:52.342
even, even up like this.

36:52.377 --> 36:54.311
If I drop this
thing, if it falls,

36:54.346 --> 36:55.879
it may be ruined.

36:55.914 --> 36:59.883
Adjust my body, see if I
can find the right spot.

37:07.159 --> 37:08.391
I'm not sure if it's on it.

37:08.427 --> 37:12.729
That's got so much
(bleep) sway to it.

37:12.764 --> 37:14.798
And it doesn't hold itself.

37:14.833 --> 37:16.900
(bleep).

37:16.935 --> 37:19.135
And I can't get it off.

37:19.171 --> 37:23.240
(groaning).

37:23.275 --> 37:24.574
I can't get it off.

37:24.610 --> 37:26.176
But now the issue is,
well, the stovepipe's stuck.

37:26.211 --> 37:27.944
It's stuck in the flashing.

37:27.980 --> 37:29.212
I can't leave it
here because if I do,

37:29.248 --> 37:30.513
it's gonna fall over.

37:30.549 --> 37:31.715
It's gonna bend all the metal,

37:31.750 --> 37:33.016
it's gonna tear my
whole chimney up.

37:33.051 --> 37:34.684
It's pretty heavy.

37:34.720 --> 37:36.419
Uh, it's also slick.

37:36.455 --> 37:38.755
Maintaining my balance for
myself and of this pipe is

37:38.790 --> 37:39.923
really difficult.

37:39.958 --> 37:41.124
I'm extremely angry.

37:41.159 --> 37:42.826
Just, uh, you know, a lot
of, it's a lot of stress

37:42.861 --> 37:44.828
compounding, so,
uh, I'm just gonna,

37:44.863 --> 37:48.131
I'm just gonna
let some of it out.

37:48.166 --> 37:49.633
I don't care if I'll die.

37:49.668 --> 37:51.701
If I fall, I fall.
That's it.

37:51.703 --> 37:56.373
(groaning).

37:56.408 --> 37:58.475
You (bleep) big heavy (bleep).

38:07.319 --> 38:08.952
(bleep).

38:08.987 --> 38:11.421
You (bleep) big heavy (bleep).

38:13.292 --> 38:15.458
When I hit a road
block, I get angry.

38:15.494 --> 38:16.626
I get mad.

38:16.662 --> 38:18.662
Uh, and I just let it
all out right on the spot.

38:18.697 --> 38:20.563
It helps me kind of
get through it quicker.

38:20.599 --> 38:23.633
(bleep).

38:23.669 --> 38:25.669
Once I kind of get
that bad energy out,

38:25.704 --> 38:27.937
then it helps me
have a level head,

38:27.973 --> 38:29.205
so I can think.

38:29.241 --> 38:30.640
Okay, yeah, I'm stuck.

38:30.676 --> 38:31.908
What do I need to do?

38:31.943 --> 38:34.311
I think I can go inside, and I
can actually feed the chimney

38:34.346 --> 38:36.546
from below, up, up.

38:36.581 --> 38:38.815
Rather than trying to do it
this way because this thing's

38:38.850 --> 38:40.216
just too heavy.

38:40.252 --> 38:41.384
I got no way to handle it.

38:41.420 --> 38:43.320
I can't get it to sit
on there correctly.

38:43.355 --> 38:46.089
So it's, um, I just
can't do it like this.

38:46.124 --> 38:48.858
Time for Plan B.

38:49.661 --> 38:52.295
It's never (bleep)
over 'til it's over.

38:54.766 --> 38:58.835
Okay. All right.

38:58.870 --> 39:01.504
Okay, now get the box off.

39:02.708 --> 39:04.808
Oh, yeah.

39:04.843 --> 39:08.211
Uh, I don't know what the
temperature is right now,

39:08.246 --> 39:11.915
just my, uh, anger
and frustration that's
keeping me warm.

39:12.684 --> 39:14.751
I was just
trying to work fast.

39:14.786 --> 39:16.353
It's getting a lot colder.

39:16.388 --> 39:18.788
That's just gonna make
all this work that
much more difficult.

39:18.824 --> 39:20.957
Yeah, and on top of that, is I
don't want my water to freeze,

39:20.992 --> 39:22.459
I don't want my
food to freeze.

39:22.494 --> 39:25.528
So I need to get this
done fast and efficient.

39:25.564 --> 39:27.163
But this is also my chimney.

39:27.199 --> 39:30.233
And this time, I wanna make
it safe and make one that will

39:30.268 --> 39:32.769
last for a lifetime.

39:32.804 --> 39:34.838
All right.

39:34.873 --> 39:37.874
Um, now I can make a fire.

39:37.909 --> 39:39.743
So, that's done.

39:39.778 --> 39:42.312
Well, that was a
really long day.

39:42.347 --> 39:46.649
It's over now, now,
now, now I got my stove.

39:50.756 --> 39:52.722
MICHAEL: When I
look at these dogs,

39:52.758 --> 39:55.091
they help me get
through the winter of Alaska.

39:55.127 --> 39:57.360
They reinvigorate my spirit.

39:57.396 --> 40:00.296
I find running and working
with these animals just as

40:00.332 --> 40:03.833
therapeutic as it is for the
animals running the miles.

40:09.207 --> 40:10.206
Come here, Mow-Mow.

40:10.242 --> 40:13.143
Right here, we got a
little bit of strong brew.

40:14.312 --> 40:18.715
So every day, there is moose
stew sittin' on the dutch oven.

40:18.750 --> 40:22.352
I dump that juice
into the dogs' water.

40:22.387 --> 40:23.853
So I bait their water.

40:23.889 --> 40:26.990
Trying to get dogs to hydrate,
you gotta trick 'em sometimes.

40:27.025 --> 40:29.626
Oh, you want some boost juice?

40:29.661 --> 40:32.028
Oh, you've been
working hard, buddy.

40:32.063 --> 40:34.330
For working animals
that endure the cold,

40:34.366 --> 40:36.466
it's a lot of upkeep.

40:36.501 --> 40:38.168
You know, I'm the coach,
I'm the mentor,

40:38.203 --> 40:39.769
I'm the leader.

40:39.805 --> 40:42.172
I'm everything to these dogs,
and they've known me since

40:42.207 --> 40:44.407
their eyes first opened.

40:44.443 --> 40:46.409
You give one of
these malamutes a job,

40:46.445 --> 40:47.811
it perks 'em up.

40:47.846 --> 40:49.646
It's what they
thrive and live for.

40:49.681 --> 40:51.848
They wanna work hard.
They're really smart.

40:51.883 --> 40:56.352
And so, it is an honor to work
with this indigenous breed for

40:56.388 --> 40:59.189
which the people of the
northwest Arctic of Alaska

40:59.224 --> 41:02.592
sculpted for
hundreds of generations.

41:03.762 --> 41:05.595
Everybody like
that strong brew?

41:05.630 --> 41:08.298
You better drink it up because
we're gonna keep runnin'.

41:08.333 --> 41:11.034
Can I get an,
"Oh, howl, yeah"?

41:11.069 --> 41:12.635
Awoo!

41:12.671 --> 41:18.675
(howling).

41:22.981 --> 41:25.582
BRITTANY: To raise a
family here in rural Alaska,

41:25.617 --> 41:28.651
it takes a lot of planning,
it takes a lot of willingness,

41:28.687 --> 41:31.688
and you can't half-heart
do anything out here.

41:34.626 --> 41:36.292
KALEB: This thing
is working great.

41:36.328 --> 41:37.827
BRITTANY: Your
little smokehouse?

41:37.863 --> 41:39.229
Moment of truth.

41:39.264 --> 41:40.430
GILBERT: Yummy.

41:40.465 --> 41:43.366
BRITTANY: Kaleb and I have
never been what someone might

41:43.401 --> 41:47.537
call traditional, including
the way we have outdoor meals.

41:47.572 --> 41:51.140
We use an ATV for
our dining room table.

41:51.176 --> 41:54.444
It's a lot of fun in
the non-traditional way.

41:54.479 --> 41:56.312
KALEB: Who wants
the other wing?

41:56.348 --> 41:58.448
ELOVIE: Me!
GILBERT: I do.

41:58.850 --> 42:01.317
BRITTANY: I think there's
nothing better than being by a

42:01.353 --> 42:03.520
bonfire, and having
the stars overhead,

42:03.555 --> 42:05.321
and being with my family.

42:05.357 --> 42:06.656
KALEB: Did you work up
an appetite, Ellie,

42:06.691 --> 42:08.324
going out on
the ptarmigan hunt?

42:08.360 --> 42:10.393
ELOVIE: I did.

42:10.428 --> 42:11.895
KALEB: We might not
have gotten a ptarmigan,

42:11.930 --> 42:14.130
but this is a
good alternative.

42:14.165 --> 42:16.432
Getting to spend the evening
with my family around the

42:16.468 --> 42:18.568
fire is awesome.

42:18.603 --> 42:21.304
And I think that the
smoker is a huge success,

42:21.339 --> 42:23.206
and I'm looking
forward to smoking many,

42:23.241 --> 42:25.008
many other meats
in the future.

42:25.043 --> 42:26.843
BRITTANY: Isn't
this skin so good?

42:26.878 --> 42:27.911
GILBERT: Uh-hmm.

42:27.946 --> 42:29.312
KALEB: Oh, man,
it worked great.

42:29.347 --> 42:31.814
BRITTANY: I'd say that
sometimes the simplest
things are the best.

42:31.850 --> 42:33.416
KALEB: Uh-hmm.

42:33.451 --> 42:35.118
BRITTANY: Are we gonna
eat this whole chicken?

42:35.153 --> 42:38.021
KALEB: Probably.
ELOVIE: Probably.

42:43.094 --> 42:44.294
ALEX: Ooh, look at that.

42:44.329 --> 42:46.763
Yeah, that sap in there,
that'll burn nice and hot.

42:47.332 --> 42:48.798
Puttin' my stove
back together,

42:48.833 --> 42:51.868
making a fire and warming up,
is a moment to savor.

42:51.903 --> 42:53.536
There we go.

42:53.572 --> 42:55.738
Now we're home free.

42:55.774 --> 42:58.141
For me, my woodstove
is like my, my shrine.

42:58.176 --> 43:00.810
When it's cold outside,
I go before my woodstove,

43:00.845 --> 43:04.047
and that's where I,
I have my prayers, right?

43:04.082 --> 43:06.482
Maybe humans have just been
like kind of living with fire

43:06.518 --> 43:09.285
for so many millions of years,
that it's just kind of in our

43:09.321 --> 43:12.322
DNA to, uh, to kind of
revere it or something.

43:12.357 --> 43:14.591
So that's one of the
reasons I came out here.

43:14.626 --> 43:16.793
I wanted to just live
by instincts, you know?

43:16.828 --> 43:19.128
I like kind of
rejecting society,

43:19.164 --> 43:21.864
and, and just going back
to kind of being an animal.

43:21.900 --> 43:23.800
You know, maybe at
some point in the future,

43:23.835 --> 43:25.935
I'll return to society.

43:25.971 --> 43:27.337
I don't really
see that happening,

43:27.372 --> 43:30.139
but at least now I know kind
of a little bit of the

43:30.175 --> 43:32.976
other way to live.

43:44.756 --> 43:46.923
JOHNNY: You want
some of the tea?

43:46.958 --> 43:48.291
The only thing I
answer out here,

43:48.326 --> 43:50.627
Mother Nature and Java.

43:50.662 --> 43:54.364
One of the toughest things at
being isolated is battling the

43:54.399 --> 43:56.699
"What ifs" in my mind.

43:56.735 --> 43:58.267
I'm facing
negative temperatures.

43:58.303 --> 44:00.169
I'm facing
animals that, you know,

44:00.205 --> 44:02.372
wanna maybe take
me or my dog out.

44:02.407 --> 44:04.140
And suddenly, you see a
bear out your window.

44:04.175 --> 44:07.310
That'll stir you up real good.

44:07.345 --> 44:11.280
I have no idea what's
gonna happen every day.

44:11.316 --> 44:13.716
It's very unpredictable.

44:13.752 --> 44:15.952
I wouldn't change
it for the world.

